SIMPLE: secant
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Secant
<hw>Se"cant</hw> <pr>(s⟦emac⟧"k⟦acr⟧nt)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>secans</ets>, <ets>-antis</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>secare</ets> to
cut. See <er>Section</er>.]</ety> <def>Cutting; dividing into two parts;
<as>as, a <ex>secant</ex> line</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Secant</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Secant
<hw>Secant</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>s⟦eacute⟧cante</ets>.
See <er>Secant</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Geom.)</fld>
<def>A line that cuts another; especially, a straight line cutting a
curve in two or more points.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Trig.)</fld> <def>A right line drawn from the
center of a circle through one end of a circular arc, and terminated by
a tangent drawn from the other end; the number expressing the ratio of
this line to the radius of the circle. See <cref>Trigonometrical
function</cref>, under <er>Function</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Secco</ent>⟦br⟧
\'d8
